11:14.533 --> 11:16.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What is the picture?

11:16.600 --> 11:19.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Give us a picture of the
financial and business
dealings other countries
do right now with

11:19.700 --> 11:21.666 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the North.

11:21.666 --> 11:23.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID COHEN, Former U.S.
Undersecretary for Terrorism and
Financial Intelligence: Well,

11:23.700 --> 11:26.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
most of it is illicit, with
the exception of the trade
with China, and that tends to

11:28.166 --> 11:33.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be in coal, in minerals
and very few other items.

11:35.166 --> 11:38.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are other countries
around the world, in Africa in
particular, in the Gulf, where

11:40.633 --> 11:43.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you have North Korean laborers
working and where you have
North Korea selling weapons

11:46.366 --> 11:48.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to these countries.

11:48.466 --> 11:52.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is in violation of U.N.
Security Council resolutions and
in violations of the sanctions.

11:54.500 --> 11:58.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And those transactions
tend to flow through
financial institutions
in China in a way that

12:01.500 --> 12:06.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is intended to be disguised
from the international
community, because they
are illicit transactions.

12:08.433 --> 12:12.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, you have
written that new sanctions could
be written, could be enacted

12:12.000 --> 12:14.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in a way that would put
real pressure on the North.

12:14.933 --> 12:17.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What would those look like?

12:17.033 --> 12:21.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID COHEN: Well, what they
would look like are sanctions
principally focused on Chinese

12:22.933 --> 12:27.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
front companies and Chinese
institutions that are
facilitating this illicit trade.

12:29.966 --> 12:34.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
If you look at the way
that North Korea engages
with the world today,
there are a few nodes,

12:36.033 --> 12:40.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
20, 40, 100 nodes, but it's a
limited sets of these companies
and these financial institutions

12:43.200 --> 12:48.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in China where the bulk of
the financial activity occurs.

12:48.166 --> 12:53.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We could focus on those nodes,
squeeze those nodes, and as a
result of that, squeeze North

12:55.000 --> 12:56.700 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Korea.

12:56.700 --> 12:57.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, John
Mearsheimer, you have
taken a look at this.

12:57.666 --> 12:59.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Do you think that could work?

12:59.800 --> 13:02.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN MEARSHEIMER, University
of Chicago: No, I don't think
sanctions will work, Judy, and

13:02.733 --> 13:04.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I think there are
two reasons for that.

13:04.833 --> 13:08.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
One is that North Korea
is not going to give
up its nuclear weapons.

13:08.566 --> 13:12.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Indeed, it would be crazy to
give up its nuclear weapons.

13:12.533 --> 13:16.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The United States is interested
in regime change, and nuclear
weapons are the ultimate

13:16.800 --> 13:18.833 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
deterrent.

13:18.833 --> 13:22.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, you would have to inflict
enormous pain on North Korea
to get it to give up those

13:25.266 --> 13:27.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
nuclear weapons.

13:27.300 --> 13:31.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, you would really
have to put tremendous
economic pressure on them.

13:33.233 --> 13:36.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And you cannot do that, in
large part because the Chinese
will not allow you to do it.

13:37.933 --> 13:40.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For China, North Korea is
a vital strategic asset.

13:40.266 --> 13:45.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For China, it's imperative
that the North Korean regime
remain in place and that the

13:45.200 --> 13:47.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
regime not be toppled.

13:47.200 --> 13:51.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Therefore, if we try to put
really significant pressure,
economic pressure, on Pyongyang,

13:53.966 --> 13:58.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the Chinese will just move in
and counter it and make sure
that the North Korean regime

13:59.600 --> 14:00.466 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
survives.

14:00.466 --> 14:02.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Let me...

14:02.500 --> 14:03.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN MEARSHEIMER: And, again,
that regime is determined
to keep its nuclear weapons.

14:03.700 --> 14:05.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: David
Cohen, what about that?

14:05.700 --> 14:09.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID COHEN: Well, John's right
that the North Korean regime
looks at the nuclear weapons

14:11.333 --> 14:15.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
programs as the guarantor
of regime survival.

14:15.200 --> 14:20.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But there is the possibility
that there is a wedge that can
be driven between the nuclear

14:21.833 --> 14:25.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
weapons program and
Kim Jong-un's desire
to stay in power.

14:25.333 --> 14:30.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the way to drive that
wedge is by putting coercive,
diplomatic and economic pressure

14:33.766 --> 14:36.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
on the regime in North Korea.

14:36.400 --> 14:40.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We will need China to
make this effective.

14:40.300 --> 14:41.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We cannot do it over
China's objections.

14:41.933 --> 14:43.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But his
point is China won't do it.

14:43.666 --> 14:46.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
DAVID COHEN: Well, I
think we have not fully
tested that proposition.

14:46.900 --> 14:51.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And one of the purposes served
by the sanctions that were done
last week and the sanctions

14:53.866 --> 14:57.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that we can do is to encourage
China to take this more
seriously and to work with us.

14:59.900 --> 15:02.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: John
Mearsheimer, why can't that
be -- why can't that happen?

15:02.300 --> 15:04.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN MEARSHEIMER: Well, let
me respond to David's point.

15:04.866 --> 15:06.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Sure.

15:06.833 --> 15:10.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN MEARSHEIMER: What President
Trump wanted to do was, he
wanted to get the Chinese to

15:10.600 --> 15:15.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
put significant pressure on
North Korea to stop these
nuclear tests and to reach some

15:17.500 --> 15:21.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
sort of modus vivendi
with the United States.

15:21.333 --> 15:24.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But the Chinese
could not do that.

15:24.066 --> 15:28.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the reason the Chinese
could not do that and the reason
they won't be able to implement

15:28.933 --> 15:33.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
David's suggested policy
is because the Chinese
have remarkably little
leverage over North

15:36.266 --> 15:37.533 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Korea.

15:37.533 --> 15:39.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And the North Koreans
fully understand that.

15:39.533 --> 15:44.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the North Koreans don't
play along with the Chinese
when they put pressure on them,

15:46.133 --> 15:49.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
because the North Koreans fully
understand that the Chinese
need North Korea to survive.

15:51.333 --> 15:55.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And once the North Koreans
understand that, it gives them
significant room to basically

15:55.866 --> 15:57.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
poke the Chinese in the eye.

15:57.900 --> 16:00.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, David Cohen,
what about his point that North
Korea -- that China really

16:00.433 --> 16:03.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
does have limited leverage,
not as much as I think some
people have been thinking?

16:03.966 --> 16:08.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID COHEN: They actually have
quite a lot of leverage, in
both the illicit and the illicit

16:10.900 --> 16:14.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
- - sorry -- the licit and
the illicit financial activity
that goes in North Korea.

16:14.000 --> 16:17.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They can squeeze North
Korea on the coal sales.

16:17.400 --> 16:21.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They can squeeze North
Korea on their illicit
financial activity.

16:21.233 --> 16:26.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They will do it to an
extent that doesn't
cause a destabilizing
situation in North Korea,

16:28.200 --> 16:32.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but they can do it in a way
that can make North Korea
more interested in a potential

16:32.600 --> 16:34.566 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
negotiation.

16:34.566 --> 16:37.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So you're
talking about threading a
needle here, John Mearsheimer.

16:37.566 --> 16:42.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It sounds like we're talking
about something in between doing
nothing and doing a lot more.

16:42.233 --> 16:47.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN MEARSHEIMER: Well, you
can do a little bit more, but
the point is to make the North

16:47.000 --> 16:52.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Koreans give up their nuclear
weapons, you have to put a
great deal of pain, a great

16:53.266 --> 16:55.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
deal of punishment on them.

16:55.400 --> 17:00.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the Chinese are not going
to play that game, because the
Chinese are heavily dependent

17:01.466 --> 17:03.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
on maintaining a
sovereign North Korea.

17:03.966 --> 17:08.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the last thing they want
to do is see the West bring
North Korea to its knees, and

17:08.633 --> 17:13.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
then see North Korea crumble,
and run the risk of South
Korea incorporating North Korea

17:14.900 --> 17:16.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
into a greater Korea.

17:16.433 --> 17:18.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This would be a strategic
disaster for the Chinese.

17:18.933 --> 17:23.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this is why we have so
little leverage over North
Korea when we try to go through

17:24.533 --> 17:25.466 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the Chinese.

17:25.466 --> 17:27.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What about that?

17:27.533 --> 17:31.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID COHEN: Well, I think
that John and I agree that it
would require an extraordinary

17:32.533 --> 17:34.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
amount of pressure to bring
the North Koreans to the table.

17:34.900 --> 17:37.033 align:left position:25%,start line:86.67% size:75%
My point is that
we ought to try.

17:37.033 --> 17:42.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The alternative is to sort of
accept a North Korea with a
nuclear weapon, with an ICBM.

17:44.100 --> 17:48.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There is the potential
that we can use pressure
working with the Chinese
to thread that needle

17:51.266 --> 17:55.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to bring the North Koreans
to the table and to find
a way to denuclearize
the Korean Peninsula,

17:57.333 --> 18:00.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which the Chinese have been very
clear about for many years is
also their policy preference,

18:02.166 --> 18:04.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
is a denuclearized
Korean Peninsula.

18:04.266 --> 18:07.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And to bring --
perhaps this would bring them
to the table to talk in that

18:07.800 --> 18:08.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
way.

18:08.800 --> 18:10.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID COHEN: Correct.

18:10.266 --> 18:10.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right,
we're not going to resolve...

18:10.933 --> 18:11.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

18:11.800 --> 18:13.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Go ahead.

18:13.300 --> 18:14.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think what we agree -- John
Mearsheimer, quick comment?

18:14.500 --> 18:16.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JOHN MEARSHEIMER: Yes,
just very quickly.

18:16.500 --> 18:20.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Let's assume that David's
right, and we can put tremendous
pressure on the North Koreans.

18:21.733 --> 18:23.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Do we really want to do that?

18:23.766 --> 18:27.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do we want to back a
nuclear-armed state run by
Kim Jong-un into a corner?

18:29.600 --> 18:32.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Isn't that the most likely
scenario where they might use
nuclear weapons, when they're

18:32.666 --> 18:34.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
desperate?

18:34.700 --> 18:38.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID COHEN: Well, I think
the most likely scenario is if
we threaten them militarily.

18:38.166 --> 18:42.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I think it's very
important we exercise restraint
militarily in the short-term.

18:42.200 --> 18:47.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think this is a long-term
plan that needs to be
implemented smartly, but
it can be accomplished.

18:49.166 --> 18:51.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I think what
everybody agrees is, there
is a lot at stake here.

18:51.700 --> 18:56.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
David Cohen, John
Mearsheimer, thank you both.

18:59.633 --> 19:04.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JOHN MEARSHEIMER:
You're welcome.

19:06.633 --> 19:11.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: In what
was perhaps the most
consequential decision
in Britain this century,

19:14.633 --> 19:19.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
voters are now having second
thoughts about their choice
to leave the European Union.

19:19.133 --> 19:24.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
A new opinion poll shows
a majority of British
people now want to stay,
and business leaders

19:26.166 --> 19:29.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
are warning their once
flourishing economy
will flounder unless
the right compromise

19:31.266 --> 19:33.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is reached with the E.U.
during exit negotiations.

19:33.400 --> 19:37.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Add to that a deeply
divided government after
the recent election has
left a hung Parliament,

19:39.300 --> 19:43.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and it has become harder for
many to keep calm and carry on.

19:43.166 --> 19:45.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Special correspondent
Malcolm Brabant reports.

19:45.800 --> 19:50.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Aldeburgh
in Eastern England,
this is Brexit beach.

19:50.766 --> 19:55.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The town's centuries'
old fishing tradition
is on its deathbed.

19:57.666 --> 20:00.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In common with kindred coastal
communities around the country,
fishermen voted to leave

20:00.866 --> 20:02.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the European Union.

20:02.900 --> 20:07.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They believe excessive
regulation from Brussels
is killing their industry.

20:10.366 --> 20:12.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One year after Britain's
so-called independence
day, Mark Foreman is
worried that the country's

20:12.633 --> 20:15.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
commitment to
Brexit is wavering.

20:15.133 --> 20:18.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK FOREMAN, Fisherman:
I thought that would
improve the fishing
situation, but now I have

20:18.500 --> 20:20.000 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
got my doubts.

20:20.000 --> 20:21.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I would have still come out
anyway for anything else.

20:21.533 --> 20:25.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I want the country to be run by
British people, not by the E.U.

20:25.100 --> 20:29.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think there's too many
people who are in power who
are against Brexit, and I think

20:29.600 --> 20:32.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there are so many people
with money tied up in Europe.

20:32.666 --> 20:36.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They just don't
want to come out.

20:36.833 --> 20:41.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: The government
has promised to revitalize the
fishing industry post-Brexit,

20:41.366 --> 20:45.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
but, in the current climate,
Kirk Stripling fears betrayal.

20:45.633 --> 20:48.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KIRK STRIPLING, Fisherman:
I'm really afraid that we
will be sold down the river.

20:48.600 --> 20:51.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They will do a deal
over something else and
sacrifice us fishermen.

20:51.400 --> 20:56.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're in a ludicrous situation,
where we only catch what is in
season at the time and which

20:56.200 --> 20:58.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is on our doorstep.

20:58.333 --> 21:01.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And quite often, we can have
loads of the fish in the sea
right here and we have got

21:01.700 --> 21:03.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
no quota to catch it.

21:03.200 --> 21:06.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So we sit here and starve to
death, while the fish swim by.

21:06.633 --> 21:11.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Polar opposite
views about Europe prevail
80 miles away in Cambridge,

21:11.233 --> 21:15.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
a historic seat of
learning and innovation.

21:15.000 --> 21:20.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is Britain's
Silicon Valley, whose
ethos is that science is
collaborative and requires

21:21.100 --> 21:24.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
an international,
frontier-free mentality.

21:24.366 --> 21:29.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But campus director
Professor Michael Wakelam
fears its cutting-edge
biotech research and

21:29.300 --> 21:34.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
development could be jeopardized
by what some perceive as the
xenophobic nature of Brexit.

21:36.366 --> 21:39.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MICHAEL WAKELAM, Professor: We
will have a reduced access to
the talent pool within Europe.

21:39.133 --> 21:44.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, secondly, what Brexit
says about our approach as a
country is that people no longer

21:45.666 --> 21:48.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
want to work with us.

21:48.266 --> 21:52.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There is a perception
that Britain is no longer
a welcoming place for
talented people to come.

21:54.500 --> 21:57.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Cambridge-based
entrepreneur David Cleevely
specializes in turning great

21:57.600 --> 21:59.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ideas into profitable
businesses.

21:59.800 --> 22:04.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
A self-proclaimed angel
investor, he disputes
the Brexit mantra that
leaving the E.U. would

22:06.766 --> 22:10.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
enable British companies
to exploit untapped markets
in the rest of the world.

22:10.233 --> 22:13.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID CLEEVELY, Entrepreneur:
We do business in some of the
most difficult countries, in

22:13.100 --> 22:17.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Pakistan, or in Nigeria
or other countries, for
example, in South America.

22:17.666 --> 22:22.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the amount of extra margin
there is there for increasing
those exports is, quite frankly,

22:25.000 --> 22:27.033 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
limited.

22:27.033 --> 22:31.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My concern about Brexit is
that we have a big market just
a few miles away, and we're

22:32.433 --> 22:35.833 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
not going to be able to access
it as freely as we could before.

22:35.833 --> 22:40.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: According
to a new opinion poll, the
result of the Brexit referendum

22:40.433 --> 22:43.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
would be reversed if
it was held today.

22:43.666 --> 22:48.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
