majority, 54 percent, would vote
to remain within the European

22:48.333 --> 22:52.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Union, and 46 percent
would decide to leave.

22:52.000 --> 22:55.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's quite clear that many
Britons regret the decision
they made last year, and perhaps

22:55.900 --> 22:59.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
wish that the Brexit
mechanism could be reversed.

22:59.966 --> 23:04.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
According to experts, that's
technically possible, but
it's unlikely to happen.

23:04.433 --> 23:09.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At Trinity College,
professor Catherine
Barnard believes the recent
election, which left Britain

23:09.333 --> 23:14.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with a minority government,
has further undermined
its hand during protracted
talks to withdraw

23:15.066 --> 23:17.066 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
from Europe.

23:17.066 --> 23:20.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CATHERINE BARNARD, Trinity
College: In reality, the U.K.
is in a somewhat weak bargaining

23:20.100 --> 23:22.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
position.

23:22.200 --> 23:24.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The famous phrase is to have
your cake and eat it, that
it would be possible both to

23:24.366 --> 23:28.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
leave the European
Union, but have the
best bits of membership.

23:28.400 --> 23:32.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's always been clear that
the E.U. wasn't going to allow
this, because why would they?

23:32.733 --> 23:37.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It's not in the E.U.'s
interests for a country
to do what the U.K. did.

23:37.000 --> 23:42.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so it's in the E.U.'s
interests, as Chancellor
Merkel has said, is
to look after the E.U.

23:43.133 --> 23:45.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
27, which means being
tough on the U.K.

23:45.700 --> 23:49.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: This monument
commemorates the Great Fire
of London, which wiped out

23:49.300 --> 23:52.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
much of England's
capital in 1666.

23:52.800 --> 23:57.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Many economists fear that Brexit
will have a similar impact on
the city of London, Europe's

23:57.433 --> 23:59.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
biggest financial
services center.

23:59.866 --> 24:04.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Japanese bank Nomura has
said it will move some of its
operations to Germany after

24:04.166 --> 24:05.166 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Brexit.

24:05.166 --> 24:07.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Others may join the exodus.

24:07.200 --> 24:11.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
This week, a city of
London delegation is
heading to Brussels to
appeal for a free trade

24:11.666 --> 24:16.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
deal to preserve a sector
that generates 12 percent
of Britain's income.

24:16.333 --> 24:20.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Jens Torpe is the Danish
publisher of a daily
business newspaper.

24:20.033 --> 24:24.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENS TORPE, Newspaper
Publisher: I think,
inevitably, that a number
of bankers and institutions

24:24.600 --> 24:26.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
would have to move
over to the continent.

24:26.733 --> 24:29.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's about half-a-million
people working here.

24:29.300 --> 24:33.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think you would see at
least some 50,000 moving out.

24:33.000 --> 24:36.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think it's going
to have quite dramatic
implications for the city.

24:36.500 --> 24:41.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The latest growth figures
for Britain put us down
on the same par as Italy.

24:43.533 --> 24:47.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We used to be number one in
the E.U., so everybody agrees
that there is a crisis coming.

24:49.933 --> 24:53.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: London's
cosmopolitan Borough
Market is flourishing
again after last month's

24:54.933 --> 24:58.333 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Islamist terror attack in which
eight people were murdered.

24:58.333 --> 25:03.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some traders favor a so-called
soft Brexit, which would permit
the continued free movement

25:03.200 --> 25:05.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
of goods and people
