abuse treatment and
related health needs.

29:01.466 --> 29:06.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Medicaid expansion under
the Affordable Care Act
provided new coverage to many.

29:08.733 --> 29:11.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Reportedly, Senator McConnell
has been considering
a $45 billion fund to
deal with opioid abuse.

29:13.666 --> 29:16.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
New Hampshire is one state
that is dealing with a crisis.

29:16.966 --> 29:21.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It has the second highest
rate of opioid deaths
relative to its population.

29:21.766 --> 29:26.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I spoke with the state's
Republican governor, Christopher
Sununu, a short time ago, and

29:26.466 --> 29:30.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
started by asking him why he
doesn't support the current
Republican Senate proposal.

29:30.466 --> 29:32.500 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

29:32.500 --> 29:34.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS SUNUNU (R), New Hampshire:
Well, I think it's important
to start off by understanding

29:34.500 --> 29:38.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that Obamacare has failed,
it is not sustainable,
it is not affordable.

29:38.933 --> 29:42.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Specifically here in New
Hampshire, the health care
exchange is really on the brink.

29:42.100 --> 29:46.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're looking at upwards
of 40 percent cost
increases to individuals.

29:46.033 --> 29:48.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
That's just not
affordable to anyone.

29:48.066 --> 29:51.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I do applaud the Senate
and the House's efforts and the
Trump administration's efforts

29:51.800 --> 29:56.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to really take Obamacare as
a reform that has to happen.

29:58.866 --> 30:00.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That being said, what they're
really doing here is, they're
kind of conflating two issues.

30:00.933 --> 30:05.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're looking at Medicaid,
traditional Medicaid entitlement
reform, which absolutely has to

30:05.166 --> 30:08.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be a viable discussion in
Congress, and Obamacare reform.

30:08.033 --> 30:10.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And they're really
putting the two together.

30:10.566 --> 30:12.833 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's the end result there.

30:12.833 --> 30:16.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The cost implications, if you
will, are really drastic to
the state of New Hampshire.

30:16.833 --> 30:20.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
You're looking at over
$1.5 billion at best
over the next 10 years.

30:20.433 --> 30:22.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's not just a challenge
for us in the state.

30:22.566 --> 30:23.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's not practical.

30:23.566 --> 30:24.833 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's just not practical at all.

30:24.833 --> 30:27.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We have no sales tax,
we have no income tax.

30:27.066 --> 30:32.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We don't have the taxes to
raise, nor would we ever want
to, like other states do.

30:33.233 --> 30:34.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So we have to find a
better solution there.

30:34.466 --> 30:36.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So I commend them for
taking up the challenge.

30:36.500 --> 30:40.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But right now, as it sits, the
Senate plan is not a viable
solution for this state.

30:40.433 --> 30:45.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Governor,
specifically with regard to
the opioid use crisis in your

30:47.466 --> 30:50.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
state of New Hampshire,
what would this bill, this
proposal mean for that?

30:50.466 --> 30:52.533 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

30:52.533 --> 30:56.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS SUNUNU: Well, we have been
on kind of ground zero, if you
will, for the opioid crisis.

30:56.266 --> 30:59.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have one of the fastest
growing economies, one of
the best qualities of life.

30:59.566 --> 31:03.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Because we are a small state,
that allows us to be very
innovative in our approach.

31:03.833 --> 31:08.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so we have been able to
sustain great success in the
state, in spite of the opioid

31:08.100 --> 31:10.033 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
crisis.

31:10.033 --> 31:12.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But part of that, when you
look whether it's Medicaid
expansion or other programs that

31:12.600 --> 31:17.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have allowed individuals to
get care, recovery services,
medical care that they otherwise

31:19.566 --> 31:22.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
may not have -- would have been
able to receive, that has been
a big boon for our state and

31:22.266 --> 31:26.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it's been a big boost to those
individuals and allowed those
doors to be opened to them

31:26.600 --> 31:29.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
in ways that otherwise
it wouldn't have.

31:29.200 --> 31:33.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, when you look at both
the cost implications,
how Medicaid expansion
right now as it's proposed

31:33.233 --> 31:37.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to being winnowed down, if
you will, over the next few
years, again, those costs are

31:37.866 --> 31:42.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
real severe and they're again
something that just is not
practical for the state of New

31:42.566 --> 31:45.133 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Hampshire.

31:45.133 --> 31:46.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What would
it mean to the program
that you have in place
now in New Hampshire?

31:46.433 --> 31:48.566 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

31:48.566 --> 31:51.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS SUNUNU: Well, when you
look at folks that are coming
through recovery or treatment

31:51.166 --> 31:53.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or folks that are looking
to fight that addiction,
you have remember
addiction with opioids is

31:53.833 --> 31:55.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
not something that you get
through in a couple of years.

31:55.866 --> 31:57.933 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a lifelong struggle.

31:57.933 --> 32:02.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's a lifelong kind of battle,
if you will, that folks have
to have the programs in place

32:03.600 --> 32:05.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
not just for six months or a
year, but for the long-term.

32:05.400 --> 32:07.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And we have to have
those recovery programs.

32:07.366 --> 32:09.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We have to have those
treatment options in place.

32:09.633 --> 32:14.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
With opioid addiction
comes some very severe
medical conditions as
well, whether liver

32:15.766 --> 32:17.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
or heart issues
that come with that.

32:17.666 --> 32:19.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Right now, we're
able to treat those.

32:19.633 --> 32:23.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're able to be preventative
with a lot of those, as opposed
to just allowing the old

32:23.000 --> 32:26.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
way of doing things where
everyone would just pile
into the emergency room.

32:26.100 --> 32:31.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, going back, taking instead
of one or two steps back,
but three or four steps back,

32:33.133 --> 32:37.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all the way to the point where
we're cutting services that,
pre-Obamacare, were in place,

32:39.066 --> 32:40.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
right, we're looking for a
system that, for New Hampshire
at least, is worse than there

32:40.933 --> 32:43.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
were even pre-Obamacare.

32:43.033 --> 32:46.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So my message to the
Senate is very clear.

32:46.000 --> 32:47.966 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Look at Obamacare reform as is.

32:47.966 --> 32:51.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Look at that program, what
we can do to reform it.

32:51.133 --> 32:55.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Understand that the opioid
crisis is affecting a lot of
states, not just New Hampshire.

32:55.100 --> 32:57.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Understand what those
implications might be.

32:57.266 --> 33:00.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not just in the funding,
but it's in the flexibilities
that states have to have.

33:00.433 --> 33:01.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

33:01.366 --> 33:02.866 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

33:02.866 --> 33:04.866 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
CHRIS SUNUNU: You have to
have a flexible system.

33:04.866 --> 33:07.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And being able to do that
will allow us as governors to
implement the programs that much

33:07.066 --> 33:09.100 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
easier.

33:09.100 --> 33:11.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, it's
been reported, as I think you
know, that the Senate majority

33:11.500 --> 33:16.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
leader, Mitch McConnell,
is looking at possibly
adding something like
$45 billion to deal

33:18.000 --> 33:22.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with opioid abuse around the
country over a period of years.

33:22.466 --> 33:23.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Would that make a difference?

33:23.533 --> 33:25.600 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

33:25.600 --> 33:28.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS SUNUNU: When you look
at $45 billion to deal with
the opioid crisis, absolutely

33:28.600 --> 33:29.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that's going to
make a difference.

33:29.600 --> 33:31.666 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's no doubt about it.

33:31.666 --> 33:36.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If it's money going in to kind
of hopefully get votes in the
Senate bill, that's a different

33:36.000 --> 33:37.000 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
issue.

33:37.000 --> 33:38.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I'm not going to sign onto that.

33:38.633 --> 33:40.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
But there is no doubt
that more resources
would help this crisis.

33:40.833 --> 33:45.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It allows recovery centers to
have more longer-term programs,
open up treatment options.

33:45.300 --> 33:49.500 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We can break down some
of the permitting process
to get more of those beds
open for individuals,

33:49.500 --> 33:51.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
peer-to-peer recovery services.

33:51.533 --> 33:55.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have been able to be very,
very innovative here in New
Hampshire, really on the cutting

33:56.066 --> 33:58.166 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
edge.

33:58.166 --> 34:00.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's how we have been
able to sustain such a growing
economy, such a high quality

34:00.366 --> 34:02.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of life, in spite of the crisis.

34:02.466 --> 34:06.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We don't want to start throwing
a wrench in those gears right
now and slow down the incredible

34:06.700 --> 34:08.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
process we have been able
to make in New Hampshire.

34:08.666 --> 34:12.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I ask you about
that money because specifically
other governors, I know

34:12.033 --> 34:16.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
John Kasich of Ohio and others
who have an opioid crisis in
their own states, have said

34:16.900 --> 34:21.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that's just not enough money
to make a difference over
a long number of years.

34:21.533 --> 34:23.566 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

34:23.566 --> 34:26.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRIS SUNUNU: Well, as I said
earlier, you know, this is
something that is not going

34:26.166 --> 34:27.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to get solved in the
next couple of years.

34:27.733 --> 34:30.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It is going to be a lifetime
issue for a lot of these folks.

34:30.266 --> 34:35.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have to have lifetime-style
programs in place to kind
of ease them not just off of

34:35.100 --> 34:39.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the opioids they're in,
making sure they have
peer-to-peer support
recovery programs, making

34:39.000 --> 34:43.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
sure they can enter the
work force and hopefully
get on better private
insurance plans, as

34:43.366 --> 34:47.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
opposed to just relying
on expanded Medicaid or
the health care exchange.

34:47.133 --> 34:51.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, when you're able to create
systems that work efficiently
-- I'm an engineer by trade.

34:51.666 --> 34:53.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I'm all about creating
an efficient system.

34:53.933 --> 34:57.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
When you're able to do that
and implement that, there is
a lot of savings you can have

34:57.266 --> 34:58.533 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
on the back end.

34:58.533 --> 35:00.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I do believe dollars can help.

35:00.100 --> 35:02.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's no doubt about that.

35:02.100 --> 35:06.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But when you look at the total
implication of this Senate
bill, $1.5 billion at best

35:06.433 --> 35:11.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
over the next 10 years, I don't
mean to sound glib, but $45
billion here and there really

35:13.400 --> 35:17.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
isn't making the dent and really
making the long-term effects
that we have to be addressing

35:17.000 --> 35:19.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
as part of a long-term
Medicaid reform.

35:19.166 --> 35:23.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Governor, one
other thing, the argument that
the Republicans in Congress

35:23.500 --> 35:28.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have made on Medicaid and
that is -- and the president's
budget director, Mick Mulvaney,

35:30.333 --> 35:34.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has said Medicaid is
unsustainable on the path that
it's on now, it's grown way too

35:36.033 --> 35:39.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
expensive, it cannot continue
like this, cuts have to come,
there has to be a change in

35:40.366 --> 35:41.100 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the trajectory.

35:41.100 --> 35:42.633 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

35:42.633 --> 35:44.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
CHRIS SUNUNU: Well,
look, I would absolutely
agree with that.

35:44.966 --> 35:48.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Look, Washington is dealing
-- the Senate and the House
and the president are dealing

35:48.100 --> 35:50.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
with nearly $20
trillion in debt.

35:50.700 --> 35:55.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
That is real money
owed to someone, and
a lot of it oversees.

35:55.266 --> 35:59.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, our spending over the
last eight years has gone
completely out of control.

35:59.500 --> 36:03.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so they do have
the challenge ahead of
them of reeling that
spending back in, creating

36:03.133 --> 36:04.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
more efficient systems.

36:04.833 --> 36:06.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Reeling it in is one thing.

36:06.900 --> 36:10.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Going above and beyond from
even where we were eight
years ago is another story.

36:10.700 --> 36:15.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that's where we kind of
draw the line and say, look,
let's deal with Obamacare here,

36:15.366 --> 36:19.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
let's deal with Medicaid
entitlement reform in another
discussion, another discussion

36:19.833 --> 36:24.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that frankly has to probably
be a longer discussion,
have to really get the
input from the states,

36:24.166 --> 36:26.600 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
nothing that should be rushed.

36:26.600 --> 36:29.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So if we can deal with
those two issues separately,
I think we can have just
much better outcomes

36:29.433 --> 36:32.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and a much more viable
solution for all the states.

36:32.733 --> 36:36.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Governor Chris
Sununu of New Hampshire, thank
you very much for talking

36:36.166 --> 36:37.166 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
with us.

36:37.166 --> 36:38.166 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
GOV.

36:38.166 --> 36:40.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
CHRIS SUNUNU: Thank you, Judy.

36:40.233 --> 36:44.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Time now for our
weekly segment on science and
technology, the Leading Edge.

36:53.466 --> 36:58.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this week, Hari Sreenivasan
is here with an update on a
pair of important stories.

36:58.000 --> 37:01.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: They are
important findings and analyses
on a pair of stories we have

37:01.966 --> 37:05.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
long been covering, the
health of bees and the
impacts of climate change.

37:05.500 --> 37:10.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A recent study looked at
the economic consequences
of climate change and
concluded it will make

37:10.200 --> 37:14.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the U.S. poorer and more unequal
if present trends continue.

37:14.633 --> 37:16.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The South would be
hit the hardest.

37:16.700 --> 37:20.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A different set of studies
looked at the health of bees in
connection to insecticides used

37:20.766 --> 37:22.266 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in crops.

37:22.266 --> 37:24.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Bees are critical for our
global food production.

37:24.500 --> 37:29.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Honeybees alone are
responsible for pollinating
$15 billion of U.S. crops.

37:31.866 --> 37:34.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The new papers demonstrated
the popular insecticide
used in agriculture
called neonicotinoids

37:35.333 --> 37:37.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
can be harmful to bees.

37:37.466 --> 37:39.566 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Miles O'Brien is with us again.

37:39.566 --> 37:43.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Miles, we have been
looking at or scientists
have been thinking
about the chemicals that

37:43.900 --> 37:48.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are used in insecticides as
kind of one of the number one
culprits for colony collapse

37:48.566 --> 37:49.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
for a long time.

37:49.800 --> 37:51.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, what is so new
about these studies?

37:51.066 --> 37:53.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well,
you're right, Hari.

37:53.100 --> 37:56.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There have been a lot of studies
in the past looking at bees
and these insecticides, which

37:56.433 --> 38:01.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
are coated on the seeds
and absorbed -- they call
it systemic to the plants.

38:03.433 --> 38:05.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have been widely used for
a decade, an alternative to
spraying insecticides on the

38:05.833 --> 38:07.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
plant as they grow.

38:07.433 --> 38:09.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
The concern is that they
can harm pollinators.

38:09.766 --> 38:13.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, so far, that's only
been a theory in the lab.

38:13.700 --> 38:18.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Separate teams in Europe and
Canada tested the possible
link between these neonics and

38:18.566 --> 38:21.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
bee losses in the field
for the first time.

38:21.066 --> 38:26.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They placed bee colonies close
to crops that had been treated
with the neonicotinoids and

38:27.200 --> 38:29.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
other colonies far
away from agriculture.

38:29.366 --> 38:33.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They sampled a variety
of specimens, pollen,
nectar, larvae, bees
themselves, of course.

38:35.333 --> 38:38.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they say the insecticide
is not only found in the crops
they are meant to protect, but

38:38.133 --> 38:43.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it spreads to other plants in
the area that are attracted
to bees, and it persists for

38:43.733 --> 38:45.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
months.

38:45.800 --> 38:48.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, how does
it affect the bees, and what
happens to the whole colony?

38:48.000 --> 38:51.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: That's the key
question, connecting those dots.

38:51.166 --> 38:56.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Researchers at York University
in Ontario did a second test
in the laboratory mimicking

38:57.033 --> 38:58.933 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
what they found in the field.

38:58.933 --> 39:02.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they exposed bees
to a small amount of the
neonicotinoids-infused pollen.

39:02.400 --> 39:07.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And those bees stopped --
get this -- maintaining
the hygiene of their hive.

39:07.066 --> 39:10.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Typically, bees will
remove sick or dead bees.

39:10.433 --> 39:14.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the insecticide-exposed
bees for some reason stopped
doing this, leaving sick bees

39:14.700 --> 39:15.966 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
inside the hive.

39:15.966 --> 39:19.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And the beehive became
a pigsty, if you will.

39:19.000 --> 39:24.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I caught up with Nadejda
Tsvetkov, one of the
lead authors of the
York University study.

39:26.100 --> 39:29.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
NADEJDA TSVETKOV, York
University: What we
found in our study was
that worker bees from

39:31.066 --> 39:34.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
exposed colonies die 23
percent sooner, so that's a
very big hit to the colony.

39:38.466 --> 39:40.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They also had abnormal
foraging behaviors.

39:40.100 --> 39:43.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We found also that the
colonies had difficulty
replacing a queen.

39:43.600 --> 39:45.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, over time, we had more and
more queenless colonies, which,
unless there is an intervention,

39:45.000 --> 39:49.966 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the colonies will perish.

39:49.966 --> 39:54.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: At first blush,
this study seems to put to rest
the neonic collapse debate.

39:57.866 --> 40:02.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, in a separate study also
published last week, a European
team found some bee colonies

40:04.766 --> 40:08.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Germany that thrived even
though they were close to fields
with neonic-treated crops.

40:10.666 --> 40:14.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This led researchers to believe
there must be other geographical
or environmental factor

40:14.733 --> 40:16.733 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
in play.

40:16.733 --> 40:19.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Maybe some bees are
more susceptible to the
toxins, depending on
their locations, for

40:19.700 --> 40:21.633 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
example.

40:21.633 --> 40:25.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In short, the studies suggests
the effects of neonics
on bees are inconsistent.

40:28.066 --> 40:30.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But that study was funded
in part by the German
chemical and pharmaceutical
giant Bayer, which

40:31.966 --> 40:34.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
happens to be the maker
of neonicotinoids.

40:34.166 --> 40:39.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Now, in a statement, Bayer
says it remains convinced that
neonicotinoid seed treatments

40:39.066 --> 40:44.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have no short- or long-term
negative effects on bees, and
that these seed treatments are

40:45.266 --> 40:47.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
useful and effective
tool for farmers.

40:47.333 --> 40:51.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: In the
totally different category of
climate science, there was a big

40:51.333 --> 40:53.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
study this week.

40:53.300 --> 40:55.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, usually, when climate
studies come out, we're looking
at environmental impacts.

40:55.600 --> 40:58.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What was interesting
about this one was, it was
looking at economic impacts.

40:58.800 --> 41:00.933 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Tell us a little bit about that.

41:00.933 --> 41:04.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, this
one is a very impressive
study on climate change.

41:04.200 --> 41:09.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Scientists in the climate realm
teamed up with economists,
the dismal science meeting

41:10.066 --> 41:12.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
climate science, if you will.

41:12.100 --> 41:16.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they looked at the economic
impacts of climate change as
you project out to the future.

41:16.133 --> 41:21.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And perhaps the most interesting
finding was that climate change
will hit different socioeconomic

41:21.866 --> 41:23.866 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
classes differently.

41:23.866 --> 41:26.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here's Berkeley scientist
and lead author of the
study Solomon Hsiang.

41:26.766 --> 41:29.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SOLOMON HSIANG, University of
California, Berkeley: In the
South, where it's hot, and

41:29.166 --> 41:33.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
along the coasts, we
might see populations
losing the equivalent
of 20 percent of their

41:33.733 --> 41:38.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
income, whereas, in the cooler
Northern and Western regions,
we actually see that populations

41:38.300 --> 41:40.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
might benefit a little.

41:40.366 --> 41:44.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And because the North tends
to be wealthier and the South
tends to be poorer, what we

41:44.100 --> 41:49.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
see is that, in the
future, climate change
is going to increase
economic inequality within

41:49.866 --> 41:51.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the United States.

41:51.400 --> 41:53.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, how
does the U.S. fare overall?

41:53.566 --> 41:57.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well, the team
estimates that for each degree
Fahrenheit increase in global

41:57.366 --> 42:02.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
temperatures, the U.S. economy
overall loses about 0.7 percent
of gross domestic product,

42:04.266 --> 42:07.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with each degree of
warming costing more than
the last as you go up.

42:07.600 --> 42:10.466 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, the U.S. as a whole is
not a winner economically.

42:10.466 --> 42:12.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: So, does
it break down by industry?

42:12.933 --> 42:16.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Say, for example,
agriculture might be hit
harder or real estate?

42:16.433 --> 42:21.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: Well,
agriculture, especially
in the Midwest, will
likely suffer immensely.

42:21.300 --> 42:23.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
That seems obvious.

42:23.333 --> 42:27.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it could be comparable to
the Dust Bowl of the 1930s,
according to these researchers.

42:28.866 --> 42:30.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Of course, real estate
on the coastline, that's
another obvious one.

42:30.300 --> 42:32.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But here's a surprise.

42:32.433 --> 42:36.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The team found the biggest
economic impact of climate
change was in health care.

42:39.100 --> 42:41.733 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They expect people living
in the South especially
will be hit more with
heat-related complications,

42:42.600 --> 42:44.666 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
like heatstroke.

42:44.666 --> 42:47.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Managing that and dealing
with the victims is, of
course, very expensive.

42:47.700 --> 42:52.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And this
is happening to a population
that's already poorer than the

42:52.200 --> 42:53.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
general average in
the United States.

42:53.500 --> 42:55.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN: And there
is the vicious cycle.

42:55.333 --> 42:56.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: All right.

42:56.633 --> 42:59.800 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Miles O'Brien, thanks so much.

42:59.800 --> 43:04.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
MILES O'BRIEN:
You're welcome, Hari.

43:06.700 --> 43:11.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally tonight:
A pair of blues greats are
collaborating on a new album

43:14.933 --> 43:16.966 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
